  "game_explanation": "This three-round, three-player bargaining game centers on two chip types: a common-value GREEN (0.50 to everyone) and a privately-valued RED (dog=0.30, buffalo=0.10, cat=0.40). Because GREEN is worth more to every player than a single RED, mutually profitable trades require exchanging unequal quantities (for example, 1 GREEN for 2 RED can increase value for both sides when the recipient values RED relatively highly or values it less but holds many RED). Buffalo, who values RED the least (0.10), is the most eager seller of RED and the natural counterparty for offers that convert GREEN into multiple REDs. Cat, who assigns the highest value to RED (0.40), demands favorable exchange rates to part with GREEN, whereas dog (RED=0.30) sits in between and will accept modestly favorable exchanges. Strategic uncertainty comes from (1) proposers not knowing others' private RED valuations, (2) multiple acceptances producing a random recipient, and (3) changing holdings across turns that constrain feasible offers. Given the player personas, dog (cooperative, stable) will repeatedly propose straightforward exchanges that look mutually beneficial on paper; buffalo (exploitation-cautious, structure-seeking) prefers trades that clearly improve his own value and will sell RED when it is obviously profitable; cat (structure-seeking, tolerant of inequality) will propose larger-quantity exchanges when those moves raise his private value. Observationally, we expect several simple 1-for-2-style exchanges (1 GREEN offered to buy 2 RED) to clear when buffalo is the counterparty, occasional multi-RED-for-multi-GREEN offers targeting dog, and some declined offers late in the game when feasible counterparties lack the required chips.",
